Dataset Shape

The dataset contains 772,516 rows and 23 columns, representing a very large traffic collision record for Toronto. Each row corresponds to a unique collision event, and each column provides a specific attribute such as time of occurrence, geographic coordinates, vehicle type involvement, or severity indicators. The large number of rows indicates a high-volume, multi-year dataset, suitable for detailed trend analysis, statistical modeling, and geographic hotspot detection.

Numerical Summary Insights

The summary statistics highlight several key patterns in the dataset:

  • OBJECTID increases sequentially from 1 to 772,516, confirming that each row uniquely represents a single collision record.
  • OCC_YEAR ranges from 2014 to 2025, with a mean of ~2019, indicating the dataset spans over 11 years of collision data.
  • OCC_HOUR has a mean around 13.5 (1:30 PM), and values range from 0 to 23, showing full 24-hour coverage. The quartiles (10, 14, 17) reveal that most collisions occur between late morning and early evening.
  • FATALITIES has a mean near 0, and the max is 4, confirming that fatal collisions are extremely rare events and heavily skewed toward zero.
  • LONG_WGS84 and LAT_WGS84 mostly reflect valid Toronto coordinates, but both have zeros, indicating some invalid or missing geographic points. These outliers require filtering before geographic analysis.
  • The projected coordinates x and y show similar issues, with zero values present, which should be excluded when plotting maps.

Overall, the dataset is large, time-rich, and mostly clean, with very few extreme values except for fatalities (rare) and some invalid location coordinates (0,0).

Missing Value Analysis

The dataset is generally very complete, with no missing values in the majority of columns. Only a few binary indicator columns contain missing values:

  • INJURY_COLLISIONS 4 missing values
  • FTR_COLLISIONS 4 missing values
  • PD_COLLISIONS 4 missing values
  • AUTOMOBILE 4 missing values
  • MOTORCYCLE 4 missing values
  • PASSENGER 4 missing values
  • BICYCLE 4 missing values
  • PEDESTRIAN 4 missing values

These columns are binary (YES/NO) variables representing involvement or severity. Missing values were replaced with "NO" to maintain consistency, since a missing severity type usually indicates the absence of that condition. All binary columns were then converted to numeric format (0/1) for accurate modeling and correlation analysis.

These columns contain only YES or NO, meaning presence or absence of a condition.

When a value is missing (NaN), you cannot leave it blank for binary logic, so you assign "NO" because:

If the collision had an injury, the value should be YES

If data is missing, it is safer to assume NO injury rather than YES injuries are rarely missing

Same for pedestrian, bicycle, passenger, etc.

Filling missing binary values with NO is a safe and logical assumption Prevents errors in next processing steps Ensures columns do not contain NaNs

In[6]:
df = df.fillna("NO")
In[7]:
#Convert YES/NO to 1/0 for modeling
binary_cols = ["INJURY_COLLISIONS","FTR_COLLISIONS","PD_COLLISIONS",
               "AUTOMOBILE","MOTORCYCLE","PASSENGER","BICYCLE","PEDESTRIAN"]

for col in binary_cols:
    df[col] = df[col].map({"YES":1, "NO":0})

In[8]:
#Distribution of Collision Hours
plt.figure(figsize=(14,7))

sns.histplot(
    data=df,
    x='OCC_HOUR',
    bins=24,
    discrete=True,
    kde=False,           # KDE disabled for discrete categories
    color='steelblue',
    edgecolor='black',
    alpha=0.7
)

plt.title("Distribution of Collision Hours", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Hour of Day (023)", fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel("Number of Collisions", fontsize=13)
plt.xticks(range(0, 24))  # ensure all hour labels appear
plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3)

plt.show()

Collisions are lowest between 12 AM5 AM when traffic is minimal.

Sharp increase after 6 AM due to morning commute.

Peak collision hours occur between 3 PM6 PM, aligning with evening rush hour.

Steady decline after 8 PM as road activity drops.

September, June, and January show the highest collision counts.

April has the lowest number of collisions.

Weather transitions and seasonal traffic patterns likely influence these fluctuations.

#Multivariate Correlation Matrix
plt.close('all')

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6), dpi=100)

cols = ['OCC_HOUR','FATALITIES','INJURY_COLLISIONS','AUTOMOBILE','PEDESTRIAN']
corr = df[cols].corr()

sns.heatmap(
    corr,
    annot=True,
    cmap='coolwarm',
    fmt=".2f",
    linewidths=0.5,
    cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.7}
)

plt.title("Multivariate Correlation Matrix", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

All correlations are very weak, meaning these variables do not strongly predict each other.

A small positive correlation exists between PEDESTRIAN and INJURY_COLLISIONS (0.31), indicating pedestrian-involved crashes are more likely to result in injuries.

AUTOMOBILE has a weak negative relationship (0.13) with PEDESTRIAN, showing vehicle-only collisions rarely involve pedestrians.

Hour of collision has no meaningful correlation with severity variables.
